  "lessons": [
    {
      "key": "Password Power-Up",
      "name": "Password Power-Up",
      "absolute_position": 1,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "overview": " [![common sense education](https://curriculum.code.org/static/img/common_sense_education.png)](https://www.commonsense.org)\n\nThis lesson was originally created by [Common Sense Education](https://www.commonsense.org/education/digital-citizenship/curriculum).\n\nStronger, more secure online passwords are a good idea for everyone. But how can we help kids create better passwords and actually remember them? Use the tips in this lesson to help kids make passwords that are both secure and memorable.",
        "preparation": "- Review instructional materials.\n- Print handout(s) for each student.\n- Prepare writing paper or notebooks for students.",
        "purpose": "Common Sense’s Digital Citizenship Curriculum addresses six core topics, based on the latest research on children, media, and technology. This lesson focuses on Privacy and Security. Students learn how to protect personal information and gain a deeper understanding of their data privacy rights so they can advocate for themselves and others.\n",
        "student_overview": "In this lesson, you'll learn about how passwords protect your information, and how to make a good password.",
        "unplugged": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Password Power-Up",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-6",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Graph Paper Programming",
      "name": "Graph Paper Programming",
      "absolute_position": 2,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **context-setting** lesson, students use symbols to instruct each other to color squares on graph paper. By \"programming\" one another to draw pictures, students get an opportunity to experience some of the core concepts of programming in a fun and accessible way. ",
        "preparation": "- (Optional) Watch the ***Lesson in Action** video.\n- Print out one ***worksheet** and ***assessment** for each student.\n- **Note:** You may want to teach an unplugged lesson on debugging before moving onto the coding lessons that follow this lesson. Have your students practice their debugging skills with an unplugged **<a href=\"https://studio.code.org/s/coursed-2023/lessons/4\" target=\"_blank\">Relay Programming lesson.</a>**\n\n",
        "purpose": "The goal of this activity is to build critical thinking skills and excitement for the course, while introducing some of the fundamental programming concepts that will be used throughout the course. By introducing basic concepts like sequencing and algorithms to the class in an unplugged activity, students who are intimidated by computers can still build a foundation of understanding on these topics. In this lesson, students will learn how to develop an algorithm and encode it into a program. ",
        "student_overview": "In this lesson, you will program your classmate to draw pictures!",
        "unplugged": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Graph Paper Programming",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_sequencing",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Introduction to Online Puzzles",
      "name": "Introduction to Online Puzzles",
      "absolute_position": 3,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, students will practice their _sequencing_ and debugging skills in maze puzzles.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "We recognize that every classroom has a spectrum of understanding for every subject. Some students in your class may be computer wizards, while others haven't had much experience at all. In order to create an equal playing (and learning) field, we have developed this \"Ramp Up Stage\" for Course D. This can be used as either an introduction or a review of how to use Code.org and basic computer science concepts. This stage covers all prerequisites needed to start Course D.",
        "student_overview": "This lesson will give you practice in the skills you will need for this course."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Introduction to Online Puzzles",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_sequencing",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Debugging with Laurel",
      "name": "Debugging with Laurel",
      "absolute_position": 4,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, students will practice debugging in the \"collector\" environment. Students will get to practice reading and editing code to fix puzzles with simple algorithms, loops and nested loops.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "The purpose of this lesson is to teach students that failure is normal when learning a new skill. Students will be given pre-written programs that do NOT work. They will be asked to fix these programs. This process, called debugging, teaches students essential problem solving and critical thinking skills. These skills transfer over as students proceed to harder and harder programming projects.",
        "student_overview": "Have you ever run into problems while coding? In this lesson, you will learn about the secrets of debugging. Debugging is the process of finding and fixing problems in your code."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Debugging with Laurel",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_sequencing",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "✨FOR LAUNCH!!!! ✨ Songwriter's Toolbox",
      "name": "Sequencing in Music Lab",
      "absolute_position": 5,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "background": "dark",
        "overview": "In this context-setting/skill-building lesson, students will explore sequencing and loops as they take on the role of a songwriter in Music Lab, layering sounds and identifying patterns to write efficient code and bring musical ideas to life."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "✨FOR LAUNCH!!!! ✨ Songwriter's Toolbox",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_sequencing",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "✨FOR LAUNCH!!!!✨ Sound Designer's Studio",
      "name": "Events in Music Lab",
      "absolute_position": 6,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "background": "dark",
        "overview": "In this context-setting, students will become sound designers using Music Lab to create interactive soundtracks with events and effects that enhance storytelling and engagement."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "✨FOR LAUNCH!!!!✨ Sound Designer's Studio",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_events",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Events in Bounce",
      "name": "Events in Bounce",
      "absolute_position": 7,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **context-setting**/**skill-building** lesson, students will learn what events are and how programmers use them in video games. Students will build a game that they can customize with different speeds and sounds.",
        "preparation": "\n - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "Events are very common in computer programs, especially in video games.  \n\nIn this lesson, students will develop their understanding of events by making a sports-based game. Students will learn to make their paddle move according to arrow keys, and make noises when objects collide. At the very end, they will get to customize their game to make it more unique!",
        "student_overview": "Ever wish you could play video games in school? In this lesson, you will get to make your own!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Events in Bounce",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_events",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Build a Star Wars Game",
      "name": "Build a Star Wars Game",
      "absolute_position": 8,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, students will practice using events to build a game that they can share.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles and find any potential problem areas.\n",
        "purpose": "CS Fundamentals is not simply about teaching computer science, it is about making computer science fun and exciting. In this series, students will learn about events using popular characters from _Star Wars_. These puzzles blur the lines between \"learning\" and \"fun\". Also, students will learn to recognize regular programming practices in games so that when they play games at home, they can see common computer science principles being used.",
        "student_overview": "Feel the force as you build your own Star Wars game in this lesson."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Build a Star Wars Game",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_events",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Dance Party",
      "name": "Dance Party",
      "absolute_position": 9,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, students will program an interactive dance party. ",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n - Consider the need for headphones. This activity relies on sound.",
        "purpose": "This lesson introduces the core CS concepts of coding and event programming (using blocks).",
        "student_overview": "Time to celebrate! In this lesson, you will program your own interactive dance party."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Dance Party",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_events",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Hardware and Software Skits",
      "name": "Hardware and Software Skits",
      "absolute_position": 10,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "In this unplugged lesson students will act out the ways internal and external parts of a computer work together. They will take on roles such as: CPU, Keyboard, Monitor, User and more.",
        "preparation": "- Print the skit outlines and cut them out for each group of students\n- Print out one classroom set of the skit roles\n- Create heterogeneous groups of students \n",
        "purpose": "The purpose of this lesson is to understand the ways internal and external parts of a computer work together to perform their functions. Today you will collaborate with a group of students to create short skits showing how various computer parts work together to complete tasks.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Hardware and Software Skits",
        "lesson_group.key": "lessonGroup-7",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Loops in Ice Age",
      "name": "Loops in Ice Age",
      "absolute_position": 11,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "This **context-setting/skill-building** lesson will quickly introduce students to loops.",
        "preparation": " - (Optional) Pick a couple of puzzles to do as a group with your class.\n",
        "purpose": "In this lesson, students will be learning more about loops and how to implement them in Blockly code. Using loops is an important skill in programming because manually repeating commands is tedious and inefficient. With these Code.org puzzles, students will learn to add instructions to existing loops, gather repeated code into loops, and recognize patterns that need to be repeated.",
        "student_overview": "In this lesson you'll use the repeat block to help Scrat reach the acorn as efficiently as possible."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Loops in Ice Age",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_loops",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Drawing Shapes with Loops",
      "name": "Drawing Shapes with Loops",
      "absolute_position": 12,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "This **skill-building** lesson builds on the understanding of loops from the previous lesson and doubles as a debugging exercise for extra problem-solving practice.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "This series highlights the power of loops with an array of puzzles meant to get students thinking about why `repeat` loops are superior to longhand.",
        "student_overview": "In this lesson, loops make it easy to make cool images with the Artist!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Drawing Shapes with Loops",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_loops",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Nested Loops in Maze",
      "name": "Nested Loops in Maze",
      "absolute_position": 13,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, students will learn how to program a loop inside of another loop.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "In this introduction to nested loops, students will go outside of their comfort zone to create more efficient solutions to puzzles.  \n\nIn earlier puzzles, loops pushed students to recognize repetition. Here, students will learn to recognize patterns *within* repeated patterns to develop these nested loops. This stage starts off by encouraging students to try to solve a puzzle where the code is irritating and too complex to write out the long way. After a video introduces nested loops, students are shown an example and asked to predict what will happen when a loop is put inside of another loop. This progression leads to plenty of practice for students to solidify and build on their understanding of looping in programming.",
        "student_overview": "This lesson will teach you what happens when you put loops inside loops inside loops."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Nested Loops in Maze",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_loops",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Conditionals with Cards",
      "name": "Conditionals with Cards",
      "absolute_position": 14,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 14,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **context-setting** lesson, students will write *conditional (if/else) statements* to state the rules of simple card games. ",
        "preparation": "- Gather decks of cards or something similar.\n- Print or display the ***sample programs**.\n- Print one ***assessment** for each student.\n",
        "purpose": "One of the best parts of teaching conditionals is that students already understand the concept from their everyday lives. \n\nThis lesson merges computer science into the real world by building off of their ability to tell if a condition is true or false. Students will learn to use if statements to declare when a certain command should be run, as well as if / else statements to declare when a command should be run and what to run otherwise. Students may not recognize the word conditionals, but most students will understand the idea of using \"if\" to make sure that some action only occurs when it is supposed to.",
        "student_overview": "It's time to play a game where you earn points only under certain conditions!",
        "unplugged": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Conditionals with Cards",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_conditionals",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Looking Ahead with Minecraft",
      "name": "Looking Ahead with Minecraft",
      "absolute_position": 15,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 15,
      "properties": {
        "overview": "This **skill-building** lesson gives students the chance to practice concepts that they have learned up to this point and get their first experience with conditionals!",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles associated with this lesson to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "This set of puzzles will work to solidify and build on the knowledge of loops, and introduce conditionals. By pairing these two concepts together, students will be able to explore the potential for creating fun and innovative programs in a new and exciting environment.",
        "student_overview": "Avoid the lava! Here you will start to learn about conditionals in the world of _Minecraft_."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Looking Ahead with Minecraft",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_conditionals",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "If/Else with Bee",
      "name": "If/Else with Bee",
      "absolute_position": 16,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 16,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, your class will continue to code with conditionals, allowing them to write code that functions differently depending on the specific conditions the program encounters.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "After being introduced to conditionals in \"Conditionals with Cards,\" students will now practice using them in their programs. The \"if / else\" blocks will allow for a more flexible program. The bee will only collect nectar *if* there is a flower or make honey *if* there is a honeycomb. ",
        "student_overview": "Now that you understand conditionals, it's time to program Bee to use them when collecting honey and nectar. "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "If/Else with Bee",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_conditionals",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "While Loops in Farmer",
      "name": "While Loops in Farmer",
      "absolute_position": 17,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 17,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, students will be working to fill holes and dig dirt in Farmer, but they will not know the size of the holes or the height of the mounds of dirt. To solve these puzzles, students will use a new kind of loop.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "As your students continue to deepen their knowledge of loops, they will come across problems where a command needs to be repeated, but it is unknown how many times it needs to be repeated. This is where while loops come in. In today's lesson, students will develop a beginner's understanding of condition-based loops and also expand their knowledge of loops in general. ",
        "student_overview": "Loops are so useful in coding. This lesson will teach you about a new kind of loop: while loops!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "While Loops in Farmer",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_conditionals",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "Until Loops in Maze",
      "name": "Until Loops in Maze",
      "absolute_position": 18,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 18,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "In this **skill-building** lesson, students will learn about \"until\" loops. Students will build programs that have the main character repeat actions \"until\" they reach their desired stopping point.",
        "preparation": " - Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n",
        "purpose": "This set of puzzles will work to solidify and build on the knowledge of loops by adding the `until` conditional. By pairing these concepts together, students will be able to explore the potential for creating complex and innovative programs.",
        "student_overview": "You can do some amazing things when you use \"until\" loops!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "Until Loops in Maze",
        "lesson_group.key": "csf_conditionals",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "End of Course Project",
      "name": "End of Course Project",
      "absolute_position": 19,
      "lockable": false,
      "has_lesson_plan": true,
      "relative_position": 19,
      "properties": {
        "creative_commons_license": "Creative Commons BY-NC-SA",
        "overview": "This **project** lesson takes students through the process of designing, developing, and showcasing new projects!",
        "preparation": "* Play through the puzzles to find any potential problem areas for your class.\n* Print out one ***Project Planning Guide** for each student (or pair).\n* (Optional) Complete your own planning guide and code your own project to show to students!",
        "purpose": "This lesson provides students with space to create a project of their own design, using a step-by-step process that requires planning but also allows for broad creativity.",
        "student_overview": "Get those hands ready for plenty of coding! It's time to start building your project."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "lesson.key": "End of Course Project",
        "lesson_group.key": "end_of_course_project",
        "script.name": "coursed-2025"
      }
    }
  ],
