  "activity_sections": [
    {
      "key": "b7aa844b-d02d-47d6-9787-236379553965",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "* **password**: a secret string of letters, symbols, and numbers that you can use to restrict who can access something digital\n* **phrase**: a group of words that go together and are easy to remember\n* **symbol**: a character other than a number or letter, such as #, !, or @.\n* **username**: a name you create to sign into a website, app, or game\n\n**Before the lesson**: As an optional activity before the lesson, have students play the [Password Protect](https://www.digitalpassport.org/password-protect.html) game in Digital Passport™ by Common Sense Education. This will help introduce key concepts of this lesson. To see more, check out the [Digital Passport Educator Guide](https://d1e2bohyu2u2w9.cloudfront.net/education/sites/default/files/tlr-asset/document-bundled-educator-guide-92018.pdf).\n\n**Ask**: _What is something in your life that you take steps to protect? Why and how do you protect it?_ ([Slide 4](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Pspz89jagbsbDvxndX0ULUKA9PikWMR3zpTSn8Cdjec/edit#slide=id.g3c3d552210_0_3))\n\nHave students think-pair-share, and then call on students to share out. Examples might include _hiding a diary_, _using a bike lock_, _keeping a toy in a safe place_, etc. Clarify that one of the ways people protect something is by restricting who can access it.\n\n**Ask**: _Let's think about when we use devices, like a phone or computer. How do you limit who can access something that you want to protect, and why would you limit access?_\n\nExamples might include password-protection, device-lock, fingerprint scanner, not letting others use the device.\n\n**Say**: _One of the most common ways to protect your devices and information online is by using a password. A **password** is a secret string of letters, symbols, and numbers that you can use to restrict who can access something digital. Some passwords, however, are stronger than others because they are harder for someone to figure out. Let's investigate why strong passwords are important and how you can make sure yours are strong._ ([Slide 5](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Pspz89jagbsbDvxndX0ULUKA9PikWMR3zpTSn8Cdjec/edit#slide=id.g3b037fe8d8_1_103))",
        "name": "Key Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b7aa844b-d02d-47d6-9787-236379553965",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a2793b7f-c02a-4094-90b3-fc2ff62a48b0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a39b80a7-779c-417e-8f94-864d00407ab6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Distribute** [If ... Then Scenarios Student Handout](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1JeZtFU6hMFTYITAAPaA_CRmOVknvkcKZQszL6u7DRG4). Tell students that they will be doing a jigsaw activity to understand WHY passwords are important.\n\n**Divide** the class into five groups and tell students this is their \"home\" group. Call on a student to read the handout directions aloud. ([Slide 6](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Pspz89jagbsbDvxndX0ULUKA9PikWMR3zpTSn8Cdjec/edit#slide=id.g3b037fe8d8_1_90))\n\n**Assign** each group one of the scenarios from the handout. Allow groups to work for five to seven minutes.\n\n**Re-divide** the class into new groups so that each  group includes at least one student from each scenario (1, 2, 3, 4, and 5). If necessary, there can be more than one person from a particular \"home\" group in an \"expert\" group. Allow five to seven minutes for each \"expert\" to present while the rest of the group takes notes. ([Slide 6](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Pspz89jagbsbDvxndX0ULUKA9PikWMR3zpTSn8Cdjec/edit#slide=id.g3b037fe8d8_1_90))\n\n**Reconvene** and ask: _Based on these scenarios, why do you think it's important to have a strong password? Take turns sharing your idea with your partner._ Allow one minute to pair-share.\n\nInvite students to share out their answers. If necessary, prompt students to refer directly to the scenarios and to the consequences that would happen if someone's password was compromised. Examples could include loss of money, people knowing your private information, identity theft, and other unknown future consequences."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a39b80a7-779c-417e-8f94-864d00407ab6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e50823fb-583c-4f63-a64c-59ded5723772"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8d839649-09ed-40bf-9460-5a2227a847a8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Say**: _The consequences we just talked about might seem scary. But there is something you can do to make sure no one can ever guess your password. Here are some important steps to power up your password._\n\n**Distribute** and project the [Power Up Your Password Student Handout](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1ihf7K4Kjupe3C0wrzzgUa-a9paNserfCfMAS2oj7178). Say: _One way to make a strong password is to start with a memorable phrase. A **phrase** is a group of words that go together and are easy to remember. We're going to do a practice round together using the phrase \"There's no way I'm kissing a frog.\" So we've already completed step one, which is to come up with a phrase._ ([Slide 7](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Pspz89jagbsbDvxndX0ULUKA9PikWMR3zpTSn8Cdjec/edit#slide=id.g3cf30f4dfd_1_114))\n\n**Invite** a student to read step two. Ask: _What word would our example phrase make?_ Invite a student to answer and add \"tnwikaf\" on the projected handout.\n\n**Repeat** steps three through five: reading the step aloud, calling on students to answer, and completing the \"Practice Round\" section of the handout. Student answers will vary as students will choose to capitalize different letters and insert different numbers. If necessary, clarify that students can insert numbers anywhere in the password.\n\n**Say**: _Now you will follow these steps to come up with a password of your own. Work independently to complete the \"Your Turn\" section of the handout._ Allow students five minutes to complete the handout."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8d839649-09ed-40bf-9460-5a2227a847a8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "5f6454ce-d5a6-4fd8-b0d0-692f94c92f54"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7e9fac4f-b2b9-4815-a3f9-e8fceae4da77",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Project** the **Password Tips** and read each one aloud. Direct students to fill in the blanks on their handout as you read them. For the last tip, clarify that a **symbol** is _a character other than a number or letter, such as #, !, or @._  ([Slide 8](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1Pspz89jagbsbDvxndX0ULUKA9PikWMR3zpTSn8Cdjec/edit#slide=id.g3d416ba77f_0_21))\n\n**Say**: _As you get older, having a strong password will become even more important. Passwords will help you protect your social networking profiles when you are in high school, keep your grades private when you are in college, and protect your bank accounts and online store accounts when you are an adult._\n\n**Have** students complete the [Lesson Quiz](https://docs.google.com/forms/u/2/d/1OBS37DZUmIxM4ZciCD6qWFMam3_u8djgZNJd9IOK6Zs/copy)."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7e9fac4f-b2b9-4815-a3f9-e8fceae4da77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d3197c58-eae2-4f90-8b29-df8add695630"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c2f10845-f55f-4000-97d3-1c49ae5180a5",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Here are additional resources you can provide students to enhance their learning:\n\n* [Family Activity](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1jzZbfj0Y1GJa6WWTHp2EEzr7t0m-Hof-qIb-QLiAcpA) \n* [Family Tips](https://www.commonsense.org/education/family-tips/k-5-privacy-and-security)\n* Facilitate a related BeakoutEDU game that was co-created with Common Sense Education, called [Lip Sync Revenge](https://platform.breakoutedu.com/game/lip-sync-revenge)! You will need to create a free account in order to access the game and related resources."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c2f10845-f55f-4000-97d3-1c49ae5180a5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "44ecc6bd-4449-4eec-b514-f33ca1456962"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e545538c-1dbf-408d-972b-f82d135ec1b6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e545538c-1dbf-408d-972b-f82d135ec1b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2069540b-07ff-4057-bc94-177cb1d714a0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e39571ba-feb6-42ef-9b8f-fbe0c965d579",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect**: _When would you need to complete a list of steps in order?_\n",
        "name": "Reflect"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e39571ba-feb6-42ef-9b8f-fbe0c965d579",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ec5c7d51-9547-4971-a147-6e9c32458b27"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "db0b8e63-e381-40e3-b84a-0c8392934b9f",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n * **Algorithm** - A list of steps to finish a task.\n * **Program** - An algorithm that has been coded into something that can be run by a machine.\n",
        "name": "Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "db0b8e63-e381-40e3-b84a-0c8392934b9f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ec5c7d51-9547-4971-a147-6e9c32458b27"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "29e60c1b-935e-48ae-a853-481cea0493ab",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Introduction” slide\n\nWatch one of the videos below to give students context for the types of things that robots can do:\n  - [Asimo by Honda](https://youtu.be/QdQL11uWWcI) (3:58)\n - [Egg Drawing Robot](https://youtu.be/slh5vMIc33I) (3:15)\n - [Dancing Lego Robot](https://youtu.be/NPIq5qldbio) (1:35)\n\nIn the Main Activity, students will encode instructions to guide each other toward making drawings without letting the rest of their group see the original image. This warm-up frames the activity for the class.\n\n\n\n",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "29e60c1b-935e-48ae-a853-481cea0493ab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ec5c7d51-9547-4971-a147-6e9c32458b27"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "32011aef-74cb-4024-ad71-bb5b302e5ede",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Discuss” slide\n\n**Discuss:** _How do you suppose that robots know how to do the things that they do? Do they have brains that work the same way that ours do?_\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Call out that while robots may seem to behave like people, they're actually responding only to their programming. Students will likely refer to robots from movies and TV that behave more like humans. Push them to consider robots that they've seen or heard of in real life, like _Roombas_, or even digital assistants like _Amazon Alexa_.\n\nWork this into a discussion on how people have to program robots to do specific things, using specific commands.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "32011aef-74cb-4024-ad71-bb5b302e5ede",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ec5c7d51-9547-4971-a147-6e9c32458b27"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "241109d0-445b-4cc4-abc0-3b74be675712",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "name": "Graph Paper Programming",
        "progression_name": "Graph Paper Programming - Video"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "241109d0-445b-4cc4-abc0-3b74be675712",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fae09383-7d6d-4e19-acb6-bce2441d9e76"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "adceb6c6-3aa3-45fa-a592-7dcac35af74c",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Graph Paper Programming - Student Resources"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "adceb6c6-3aa3-45fa-a592-7dcac35af74c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fae09383-7d6d-4e19-acb6-bce2441d9e76"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c590b1fa-e516-4b15-a429-9f059989232a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "In this activity, students will act as both programmers and robots, coloring in squares according to programs that they have written for one another.\n\n**Distribute:** Students will use 4x4 grids (or sheets of graph paper with 4x4 boxes sectioned off). They will also need the image worksheet.\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Graph Paper Programming - Commands” slide\n\n**Do This:** Project these commands, or write them on the board.  They won't persist long, but they will help students make the transition from Algorithm to Program.\n \n    Move one square right\n    Move one square left\n    Move one square up\n    Move one square down\n    Fill in square with color\n\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c590b1fa-e516-4b15-a429-9f059989232a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2d45548c-46bd-44d4-986e-e2c4050ec1e0",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today we all get to program robots...and they're already here in the room! It's you! We're going to write programs using symbols with special meanings to help each other recreate a picture. First, we'll practice together as if I am the robot and you are the programmers, then we can break up into groups so that everyone gets a turn.\n\n\n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2d45548c-46bd-44d4-986e-e2c4050ec1e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d1995e1-82f4-417b-8510-f88e24c6c66c",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Graph Paper Programming - Puzzle #1” slide\n\nDisplay both the image that you are going to have the students walk you through, and a blank grid that you will fill-in with your ARM. Make sure that the instructions, grid, and image remain visible at the same time. When the direction “fill in square with color” is given, drag one of the two squares on the slide onto the grid to represent a square filled in with color.\n\n![](https://code.org/curriculum/docs/csf/c2_GraphPaper1.png)"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d1995e1-82f4-417b-8510-f88e24c6c66c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c74929ac-3087-452f-9a6b-cf6908f00e0f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "_Here is an image.  Pretend that I am the robot with an Automatic Realization Machine (ARM).  These are the only instructions that I understand._\n\n_Starting at the upper left-hand corner, guide my ARM out loud with your words._",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c74929ac-3087-452f-9a6b-cf6908f00e0f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "31a7df6b-b5a7-472e-a5a2-b2913e25da55",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Model:**  The class might give you instructions like these below.  As you hear an instruction that you intend to follow, make sure to repeat it out loud so that the students can keep track of what you are doing. \n\n    Move One Square Right\n    Fill In Square with Color\n    Move One Square Right\n    Move One Square Down\n    Fill In Square with Color\n\nContinue with the activity until you have completed your sample square. \n\n\n**Capture:** Write each of the commands down so that students can see all of the steps that went into the one image.\n\n    Move One Square Right\n    Fill In Square with Color\n    Move One Square Right\n    Move One Square Down\n    Fill In Square with Color\n\n\n**Say:** _You just gave me a list of steps to finish a task. In programming, they call that an algorithm.  Algorithms are great, because they are easy for you to understand as the programmer. BUT, what happens when we want to write down the algorithm for a drawing like this?_\n\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Graph Paper Programming - Puzzle #2” slide\n\nShow the students a more complicated image, like the one below. Feel free to use the \"List of steps\" table in the slide to write down the steps students suggest.\n\n![](https://studio.code.org/blockly/media/curriculum/docs/csf/c2_GraphPaper2.png)\n\nNext, begin writing down some of the instructions that it would take to replicate that image.  Hopefully, students will see that writing everything out longhand would quickly become a bit of a nightmare.\n\n    Move One Square Right\n    Fill In Square with Color\n    Move One Square Right\n    Move One Square Right\n    Fill In Square with Color\n    Move One Square Down\n    Move One Square Left\n    Fill In Square with Color\n    Move One Square Left\n    Move One Square Left\n    Fill In Square with Color\n    PLUS 12 MORE INSTRUCTIONS!\n\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show next slide\n\nShow the students this list of symbols.\n\n![](https://studio.code.org/blockly/media/curriculum/docs/csf/c2_GraphPaper3.png)"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "31a7df6b-b5a7-472e-a5a2-b2913e25da55",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "cc541bcc-9e65-42e8-b9ef-0d1b42add15f",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Discuss:** _How could we use these symbols to make our instructions easier?_"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "cc541bcc-9e65-42e8-b9ef-0d1b42add15f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "24828afc-2b96-4ee1-b033-5b3b7a1b31b6",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Draw out ideas that relate to transitioning from the verbal instructions to the symbols. Once the students get to that place, point out that this text:\n\n- “Move one square right, Move one square right, Fill-in square with color”\n\nwould now correspond to the program:\n\n![](https://levelbuilder.code.org/curriculum/course2/1/program.png)\n\n**Discussion Goal:** Get at the idea that students can use symbols to stand for entire phrases.  Once they understand that, share with them that making the switch from listing steps in detail to encoding them is called **\"programming.\"** "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "24828afc-2b96-4ee1-b033-5b3b7a1b31b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2768cf48-bf4b-4969-b059-87fbef602a29",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show next slide\n\n**Model:** Now, have the class help you draw the larger image using only symbols.  Do not worry about unnecessary steps for now.  If their final program works to create the image, consider it a win. (The symbols are infinitely cloned on this slide for your use in modeling this puzzle.)\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Notice that we have written our program from left to right like you would read a book in English.  Some students prefer this method.  Others like to start each line of the grid on a new line of paper.  The way they write their program doesn't matter as much as whether the other people in their groups can follow along!\r\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2768cf48-bf4b-4969-b059-87fbef602a29",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "17c43129-a4e9-4758-9c68-8e443481fcdc",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "The classroom may be buzzing with suggestions by this point. If the class gets the gist of the exercise, this is a good place to discuss alternate ways of filling out the same grid. If there is still confusion, save that piece for another day and work with another example.\n\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Sample Solution” slide\n\n\n![](https://studio.code.org/blockly/media/curriculum/docs/csf/c2_GraphPaper4.png)\n\n\n---"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "17c43129-a4e9-4758-9c68-8e443481fcdc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fda185bc-97d7-4a31-970d-519be991c63b",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Your Turn!” slide.\n\n\n&nbsp\n\n\n###The Students' Turn\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Activity Sheet” slide\n\n\n**Group:** Divide students into pairs or small groups.  \n\n- Have each pair/group choose an image from the worksheet.\n- Discuss the algorithm to draw chosen image with partner(s).\n- Convert algorithm into a program using symbols.\n- Trade programs with another pair/group and draw one another's image.\n- Choose another image and go again!\n\n![](https://code.org/curriculum/docs/csf/c2_GraphPaper7.png)"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fda185bc-97d7-4a31-970d-519be991c63b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c3e50f21-755c-47e4-a338-458ccc3213ac",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show next slide if using the Optional Assessment\n- Hand out ***Graph Paper Programming - Assessment** and allow students to complete the activity independently after the instructions have been well explained.\n- This should feel familiar, thanks to the previous activities.",
        "name": "Optional Assessment (10 minutes)"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c3e50f21-755c-47e4-a338-458ccc3213ac",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4c68b1ae-5e01-4163-8612-7ee3d8b9d4df"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "146ca04a-b590-40e4-b197-3bd842aae719",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:**\n\n \n - _Draw another image that you could code. Can you write the program that goes with this drawing?_\n - _What other types of robots could we program if we changed what the arrows meant?_",
        "name": "Reflection",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Reflection prompts like these can be completed in a variety of styles. Journaling or discussion (with groups or partners) are great options!"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "146ca04a-b590-40e4-b197-3bd842aae719",
        "lesson_activity.key": "327ddbcc-f916-4a7a-a0de-44b300a73632"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "261a5597-7096-4ad7-b1b2-f0240334a3e0",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Use these activities to enhance student learning. They can be used as outside of class activities or other enrichment.\r\n\r\n**Better and Better**\r\n\r\n- Have your class try making up their own images.\r\n- Can they figure out how to program the images that they create?\r\n\r\n**Class Challenge**\r\n\r\n- As the teacher, draw an image on a 5x5 grid.\r\n- Can the class code that up along with you?"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "261a5597-7096-4ad7-b1b2-f0240334a3e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "13d9a98e-d8cb-4c88-bc0d-94bbc451e3b2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6efcf15f-60f5-43d9-b7a3-ae8fee54b966",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** _Why is it important to give a robot specific instructions when you “program” it?_\n\nStudents will either be learning a lot of new concepts or reviewing a lot of basic concepts. Based on your class's experience, you can cover the following vocabulary or move on to a bridging activity. We recommend using the following words in sentences if the definitions aren't explicitly covered.",
        "name": "Reflect"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6efcf15f-60f5-43d9-b7a3-ae8fee54b966",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fab37ddc-e1a4-42a2-96df-b5706a5c8dc3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "44d57e65-7343-40ee-b2fa-c5933bc6d393",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n\nThis lesson has the following important vocabulary words:\n\n\n\n - **Bug** -    An error in a program that prevents the program from running as expected. \n\n - **Debugging** -    Finding and fixing errors in programs. \n\n - **Loop** -    The action of doing something over and over again\n\n - **Program** -    An algorithm that has been coded into something that can be run by a machine.\n\n - **Programming** -    The art of creating a program. ",
        "name": "Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "44d57e65-7343-40ee-b2fa-c5933bc6d393",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fab37ddc-e1a4-42a2-96df-b5706a5c8dc3"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ed2a4f2-b36c-402a-b257-4f8029176d01",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "This activity will help bring the unplugged concepts from \"Graph Paper Programming\" into the online world that the students are moving into."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ed2a4f2-b36c-402a-b257-4f8029176d01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0e680b41-9c00-40e2-ad3d-0e6d18e21273"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7b485062-a372-48d5-81a4-08b5979ac62b",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show the next slide\n\nPull up a puzzle from the lesson. We recommend puzzle 6 for this activity. Break up the students into groups of three or four. Have them \"program\" Red, the angry bird, to get to the pig using arrows from \"Graph Paper Programming.\"\n\n![](https://studio.code.org/blockly/media/curriculum/docs/csf/c2_GraphPaper3.png)\n\nThe class will not need to use the last arrow.\n\nOnce all the groups have an answer, discuss the path as a class.",
        "name": "Preview of Online Puzzles as a Class\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7b485062-a372-48d5-81a4-08b5979ac62b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "0e680b41-9c00-40e2-ad3d-0e6d18e21273"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "765dd023-0c62-4224-964c-69b6b3faedfa",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "name": "Online Puzzles",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Show the students the right way to help classmates:\r\n\r\n - Don’t sit in the classmate’s chair\r\n - Don’t use the classmate’s keyboard\r\n - Don’t touch the classmate’s mouse\r\n - Make sure the classmate can describe the solution to you out loud before you walk away\r\n\r\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "765dd023-0c62-4224-964c-69b6b3faedfa",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1df2e554-3adb-4f33-89f1-da72ce89bdf5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5369014a-d431-4197-8caa-bcb78eb2c2c1",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Teachers play a vital role in computer science education and supporting a collaborative and vibrant classroom environment. During online activities, the role of the teacher is primarily one of encouragement and support. Online lessons are meant to be student-centered, so teachers should avoid stepping in when students get stuck. Some ideas on how to do this are: \n\n - Utilize Pair Programming whenever possible during the activity.\n - Encourage students with questions/challenges to start by asking their partner.\n - Unanswered questions can be escalated to a nearby group, who might already know the solution.\n - Have students describe the problem that they’re seeing. What is it supposed to do? What does it do? What does that tell you?\n - Remind frustrated students that frustration is a step on the path to learning, and that persistence will pay off.\n - If a student is still stuck after all of this, ask leading questions to get the student to spot an error on their own."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5369014a-d431-4197-8caa-bcb78eb2c2c1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1df2e554-3adb-4f33-89f1-da72ce89bdf5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fe1de214-4c98-4655-a362-8d8a8974fc08",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Maze Intro: Programming with Blocks” video",
        "progression_name": "Video: Maze Intro: Programming with Blocks"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fe1de214-4c98-4655-a362-8d8a8974fc08",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1df2e554-3adb-4f33-89f1-da72ce89bdf5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f18516a7-be48-451f-934b-d5ccdc279941",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 2-7 - Skill Building” slide",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f18516a7-be48-451f-934b-d5ccdc279941",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1df2e554-3adb-4f33-89f1-da72ce89bdf5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "97816bd9-d69f-4945-9f41-149314c2b587",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Decompose It!” slide\nWhile they are working on a solution to the following challenges, encourage students to press the Run button frequently to see how far the bird gets and to make it easier to see what code to add next. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 8-10 - Challenge” slide",
        "progression_name": "Challenge/Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "97816bd9-d69f-4945-9f41-149314c2b587",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1df2e554-3adb-4f33-89f1-da72ce89bdf5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "80da96c4-0231-4d63-8fe9-419dbdefaee3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n\n**Reflect**\n\n - *Why is it important to program your blocks in a specific order?*\n",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "80da96c4-0231-4d63-8fe9-419dbdefaee3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "fcc3cef2-b9f1-4840-bd2a-353c3e25e0f9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec87cb3b-2f09-485c-8d19-93c6b5032b17",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect**: *When have you learned a new skill and faced failure?*\n\nOne of the most important parts of learning to program is learning to debug. Ask the class if they have ever learned a new skill and faced failure.\n\nFor example:\n\n - Learning to ride a bike and falling down\n - Learning to bake and burning the food\n - Learning to play a sport and not winning a game\n\nFacing failure is very common when learning new things. Have students discuss past failures and how they overcame them.\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n\nIn programming, computer scientists often run into \"bugs\" in their code.\n\n - **Bug**: Part of a program that does not work correctly.\n\nA bug can really mess up the program, so it's important to learn to \"debug\" your code.\n\n - **Debugging**: Finding and fixing problems in your algorithm or program.\n\n- **Decompose:** Break problems down into smaller steps. \n\nProblems in and outside of computer science usually need to be broken down into smaller tasks. This will help  you figure out what to do one step at a time. \n\nContinue the conversation if you think your class needs more of an introduction, but leave time for one of the bridging activities.",
        "name": "Introduction\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec87cb3b-2f09-485c-8d19-93c6b5032b17",
        "lesson_activity.key": "3c83702a-80ea-4e8e-8220-c39df987406b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0c7e61bb-f11d-4315-b628-be9d61f0ee77",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Bridging Activity” slide\n\nThese activities will help bring the unplugged concepts from \"Debugging Unplugged: Relay Programming\" into the online world that the students are moving into. Choose one of the following to do with your class:"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0c7e61bb-f11d-4315-b628-be9d61f0ee77",
        "lesson_activity.key": "35542cd5-51f5-4920-8a59-12f34c3560ff"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a0d1fce1-7c46-461f-ab87-7c7ebc894444",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Break your class up into teams of 3-5 and go to a large space. This space could be in a gym or outside. Queue up these teams like in \"Relay Programming\". Pick a semi-difficult design from ***Activity Packet**. Display this design at the end of a long distance between each team. Along with the display, provide each team with enough paper blocks from ***Manipulatives**. Each team will need plenty of `fill 1` and `move ___` blocks. The `move ___` blocks can either be filled in ahead of time, or filled in during the game. Either way, make sure these blocks are properly defined when the game is playing out.\n\nOnce all the teams are lined up, display or read out the following rules:\n\n- The first student in line gets to run over to the image, review it, and place the first code block in the program to reproduce that image.\n- The first student then runs back and tags the next person in line, then goes to the back of the queue.\n- The next person in line dashes to the image, reviews the image, reviews the program that has already been written, then either debugs the program by taking out an incorrect code block, or adds a new block in. That student then dashes back to tag the next person, and the process continues until one group has finished their program.\n\nMake sure the students are only using the `fill 1` or `move ___` blocks, and only placing one down per turn. The first team to _correctly_ write out the code for their image wins.\n\n####-Or-",
        "name": "Unplugged Activity with Paper Blocks\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a0d1fce1-7c46-461f-ab87-7c7ebc894444",
        "lesson_activity.key": "35542cd5-51f5-4920-8a59-12f34c3560ff"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0762ba74-cd57-44d8-a785-00ffbf881354",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Group the students into teams of 3. Choose a puzzle from the lesson. We recommend the fifth puzzle. Have the students in each team sit at a computer with the puzzle displayed. Each team only gets one computer and only one student can be looking at the screen. Display or read the following rules:\n\n - Only one student in each team can look at the screen. \n - This person can only delete or add one block at a time. Once that person has added or removed a block, they can tap the shoulder of the next person.\n - The next person can proceed to play out their turn.\n - No turns can be skipped or repeated, everyone must play an equal amount.\n\nThe first team to finish the puzzle *correctly* wins!",
        "name": "Preview of Online Puzzles as a Class\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0762ba74-cd57-44d8-a785-00ffbf881354",
        "lesson_activity.key": "35542cd5-51f5-4920-8a59-12f34c3560ff"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6a93abe9-74d5-438b-8ef7-8f232d687565",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "It might be helpful for students to sit with their teams from the bridging activities. Every student should work on these puzzles individually or in pairs, but having a closely knit group to ask and answer questions with can help develop confidence and understanding with the subject matter.",
        "name": "Debugging with Laurel"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6a93abe9-74d5-438b-8ef7-8f232d687565",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81ddc725-a367-4d73-8397-7b3b140f7d83"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "63822c99-7e7a-4f9e-911c-69dbc4c1f07a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “De-bugging with the Step Button” video\n",
        "progression_name": "Video: De-bugging with the Step Button"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "63822c99-7e7a-4f9e-911c-69dbc4c1f07a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81ddc725-a367-4d73-8397-7b3b140f7d83"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "baa6b735-72bb-40d8-986c-a394a7801d7b",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 2-6 - Skill Building” slide",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "baa6b735-72bb-40d8-986c-a394a7801d7b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81ddc725-a367-4d73-8397-7b3b140f7d83"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e5187bcc-85db-4245-8235-adfda0882f3a",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Decompose It!” slide\nRemind students to try coding one block at a time, and press Run frequently in order to break the following challenges down into small steps. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 7-9 - Challenge” slide",
        "progression_name": "Challenge/Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e5187bcc-85db-4245-8235-adfda0882f3a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "81ddc725-a367-4d73-8397-7b3b140f7d83"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e4a9ee73-ba89-48bc-8c51-7fe4dc18c125",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide. \n\nHaving students write about what they learned, why it’s useful, and how they feel about it can help solidify any knowledge they obtained today and build a review sheet for them to look to in the future.\n\n**Reflect:**\n\n - *How does working with other people help you debug your program?*",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e4a9ee73-ba89-48bc-8c51-7fe4dc18c125",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e560de9e-651e-447c-8214-6a46daa402d4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "44992618-3abd-4116-8447-d9c068bd8f00",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g351fe46eccc_1_1\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Reveal one vocabulary term & definition at a time. Briefly introduce each term as a preview of what students will learn in this lesson.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g31437c77914_0_90\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Reveal one vocabulary term & definition at a time. Briefly introduce each term as a preview of what students will learn in this lesson.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_23\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> Why do you think it’s important to give computers instructions in the right order? What do you think would happen if we gave instructions out of order?\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> This question encourages students to think about how computers can’t think for themselves—they only follow each step exactly as written. It helps them realize that, unlike humans, computers can't guess or adjust if instructions are mixed up.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_19\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Introduce the objectives of this lesson. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Today, we’re going to make music using code! Just like a song needs the right notes in the right order to sound great, a computer needs to be able to read a program with the right steps in the right order to work. You’ll be choosing the steps and creating a sequence that makes your music play just how you want.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_14\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Introduce students to the activity, The Sequence Shuffle, and remind them of the definition of sequence – the order of steps in a program or task.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> In this activity you will start with an example of a task that can be done in three distinct steps. The task is only successful if the steps are done in a specific order.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Click to reveal each step and then the picture of a successfully prepared bowl of cereal.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g315a9df97f0_0_20\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Now, have the class consider what would happen if those same steps were done in a different order such as pouring the milk before getting the bowl and spoon. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> What is the difference when the order of these steps changes? \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Students will start to understand the importance of carefully sequencing steps for a task and will later apply that to sequencing their code.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g315a9df97f0_0_31\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Have students get into small groups of 2-3.  \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Now it’s your turn to write the steps for one of these tasks! Look at the three pictures here and choose which task you will write steps for. Then, work together to write the steps someone would need to do to be successful. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Circulate:</strong> Support students in writing simple steps. The priority of this activity is in reflecting on the order of the steps more than writing the steps at this time. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Great! You have three simple steps that if done in order, will complete the task. But what if you did the same steps in a different order? Draw a picture (or discuss) what the outcome would look like if the steps were done out of sequence. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br />Teacher Tip: Have students discuss in groups, and then share out. Assign one person in each group to be the secretary (responsible for taking notes) and another to be the spokesperson (responsible for sharing the group's ideas with the class). Provide a printed copy of the slide for them to write on during the discussion.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g31fbcde91da_0_3\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Do any of your instructions happen more than once? How could we explain that some steps need to be repeated a certain amount of times?\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g315a9df97f0_0_40\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Finish the warm up activity with an explanation of how computers follow instructions in order. They will be practicing sequencing code in the next activity in Music Lab.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "44992618-3abd-4116-8447-d9c068bd8f00",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cfeeee38-51b5-4a44-ae15-8f7b3f16b80d"
      }
    },
