    {
      "key": "b1698b55-f62c-4853-abb5-f9d5cafc33a3",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_27\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      Activity\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_30\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Watch the video on the slides together as a class. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> How might songwriters use code to help them make music\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Students will begin to see a connection between songwriters and coding and how order or sequencing is important in both.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_127\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Give students an introduction to the lab on this level with a demonstration that includes: \n\t\t<br />Where/how to read the instructions \n\t\t<br />Activate Speech to text by clicking on the speaker in the bottom right corner \n\t\t<br />Where the Run button is to start the program.\n\t\t<br />Point out the timeline and how it changes as you add coding blocks\n\t\t<br />Show students how to click on the blocks to change sounds \n\t\t<br />Show how to move blocks around, change the order and delete as needed\n\t\t<br />Show how to click on the light bulb for a hint\n\t\t<br />Demonstrate reading the feedback message if the code isn’t quite correct yet\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><strong>Transition:</strong> Have students transition to continuing the lesson on their own devices. They will work on levels 2-6 independently. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br />Teacher Tip: Allow students ample time to explore all the available sounds so they become familiar with their options.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_163\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Watch the video together as a class. Use the next slide to pause and review/reinforce any musical concepts your students may need further clarification on.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a057cd68_0_50\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> What is a measure? What’s the difference between the `play together` and the `play sequential` blocks? What is a rest?\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Review and reinforce the main points from the video. This gives your class a chance to make a strong connection to how songwriters would use a tool like Music Lab in their careers and also introduce them to musical terms used in the lab in the following levels. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br />Teaching Tip\n\t\t<br />A common misunderstanding in Music Lab is the difference between `play sequential` and `play together`. \n\t\t<br />`play sequential` plays each sound one after the other, in the exact order you list them—like steps in a song.\n\t\t<br />`play together` plays all the sounds at the same time, creating a layered or harmonized effect—like a band playing multiple instruments in unison.\n\t\t<br />Understanding the difference helps students control the timing and feel of their music more effectively.\u000bA measure is a small chunk of music that helps keep the beat organized.\n\t\t<br />A rest is a silent space in music where no sound is played.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a057cd68_0_17\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Level 10 is an opportunity to check for understanding in the class.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a057cd68_0_34\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> This level has choices of three short videos to connect computer science to a songwriter career. Limit or expand the time spent on this level as needed for your class.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_49\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> This level has two choices of songs with the code ready to explore. Use this level as review, exposure, and/or inspiration and expand or limit the time spent on this level as needed for your class.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a057cd68_0_68\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <strong>Transition:</strong> Have students spend the remainder of the class time using what they’ve learned to create their own music. The instructions include some suggestions for what their project should include.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b1698b55-f62c-4853-abb5-f9d5cafc33a3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "de11f26e-fbe1-474d-94f2-153c4c5a5b84"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b9a4b28c-47ef-4633-a1c9-504922226fb6",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_38\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Review the objectives of the lesson. Have students show a thumbs up/down/sideways to reflect on whether they reached each objective.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g310cce97867_0_46\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Introduce the Mystery Melody activity. First, press the speaker icon on the slide to play the melody out of sequence.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> What did you notice when the notes were out of order?\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> This helps students articulate why sequencing matters and reinforces how things feel “off” without the right order.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Thent, press the second speaker icon on the slide to reveal the melody with the notes in the correct order.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g31437c77914_0_71\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Have students set up for a quick Turn & Talk to reexamine the Question of the Day. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Take turns listening and answering the Question of the Day. Give me a thumbs up after you both have shared your answers.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_236\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> This is an optional activity to encourage your students to share the creative music they’ve built with code. Consider adding an opportunity for students to share ‘glows and grows’ after they share their projects with each other.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b9a4b28c-47ef-4633-a1c9-504922226fb6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c8c0f007-734b-49b2-a4da-4c16d9c040c0"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "19887941-15e9-47ea-ab84-a7d59814c432",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g1b0012b9552_0_235\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> How can we make our programs more interactive and expressive?\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Get students thinking about how they can make their programs more fun and creative by adding ways for people to interact with them. Help them imagine how cool it would be if their music changed when someone pressed a key or clicked a button, setting the stage for adding interactivity to their projects.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g1b0012b9552_0_230\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Introduce the objectives of this lesson. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Welcome to our final lesson! Today, you get to experiment with using music to set the scene of a game or a movie. We will be making our music programs more interactive by adding events.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_34\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Set students up to play Simon Says [Sounds Edition] using the instructions and example commands on the slide. Rotate the leader, Simon, for as long as time allows. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> This game works similarly to the way events work in computer programming. We were always waiting for the trigger (“Simon Says”) to tell us we should do an action. If the trigger wasn’t there, we didn’t do anything.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_52\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Finish the warm up activity with an explanation of how events can be used to make code more interactive and respond to user inputs. They will be practicing customizing and creating events in code in the next activity in Music Lab.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "19887941-15e9-47ea-ab84-a7d59814c432",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1d675c6f-8126-4ec8-b4b9-3edd016a3c79"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2e4daff6-af42-44e2-b692-ced8a1b9cb6a",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Intro Video"
