    {
      "key": "d633d6c9-064a-4f6a-978a-525b87d4218c",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Freeplay"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d633d6c9-064a-4f6a-978a-525b87d4218c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b9abe28-1735-44ac-a458-aec6dc2540d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "07722f28-ebe2-487e-a92e-2604d61e2485",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_60\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Watch the video on level 1 together as a class. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> Discuss other creative jobs that connect music and technology\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Students might think of how a sound designer uses technology to create sound effects for movies and video games. They use special software to mix sounds and make everything sound realistic. Another example is a music producer, who uses digital tools to edit and improve songs before they are released.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_76\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Read the instructions for level 2 together as a class. Important tips to point out:\n\t\t<br />Guide students to notice the green event triggers. \n\t\t<br />Events stand alone and do not connect to the main program. \n\t\t<br />The sounds connected to events only play when the button (on the keyboard or on screen left of Run) is pressed. \n\t\t<br />Make a connection to the Simon Says activity in the warm up and encourage students to consider the use of a event to make the program interactive and fun.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><strong>Transition:</strong> Have students transition to continuing the lesson on their own devices. They will work on levels 3-10 independently.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g328a7af70e4_0_92\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-microphone\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Say:</strong> Read the instructions for each level and try to complete the code. Press the Run button to try it out. If something is not quite right you will get a hint under the instructions. When you’ve successfully completed the challenge, a new message and a Continue button will appear. Click Continue to move to the next level and move at your speed. \n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-refresh\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Circulate:</strong> Encourage students to read the instructions and hints on each level as you circulate. Ask guiding questions to support students if they get stuck.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_168\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Level 8 is an opportunity to check for understanding in the class. It may be helpful to bring the class together to discuss misconceptions.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_205\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <strong>Transition:</strong> Have students spend the remainder of the class time using what they’ve learned to create their own music. The instructions include some suggestions for what their project should include.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "07722f28-ebe2-487e-a92e-2604d61e2485",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9b9abe28-1735-44ac-a458-aec6dc2540d2"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f382c4ac-f3d2-46f9-bbf6-d26a92ec9202",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<table>\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\">Slide</td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">Lesson Guide</td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g111726a1132_0_199\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Review the objectives of the lesson. Have students show a thumbs up/down/sideways to reflect on whether they reached each objective.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g1b0012b9552_0_737\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Review the question of the day.\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-comments\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discuss:</strong> How did we make our programs more interactive and expressive?\n\t\t<br />\n\t\t<br /><i class=\"fa fa-lightbulb-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Discussion Goal:</strong> Encourage students to reflect on how they made their programs more fun and creative by adding ways for people to interact with them. Have them share examples of the sounds and events they used and why.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g2694c47731d_3_41\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> Give students time to write their reflections on paper or any avenue you prefer. If time allows have them share at least one reflection with a partner and and then submit the reflection to you.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n  <tr>\n    <td style=\"width: 25%\"><img src=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw/export/png?id=19-FrZQ7OwIOjHc_63UrEa46u1_PiETcR4QYwAi0CIRw&pageid=g350eaf66457_0_223\"></td>\n    <td style=\"width: 75%\">\n      <i class=\"fa fa-check-square-o\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> <strong>Do This:</strong> This is an optional activity to encourage your students to share the creative music they’ve built with code. Consider adding an opportunity for students to share ‘glows and grows’ after they share their projects with each other.\n    </td>\n  </tr>\n\n</table>    \n    "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f382c4ac-f3d2-46f9-bbf6-d26a92ec9202",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2fb06b91-2ec8-42c2-9934-78900b154834"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6c6f5b48-6013-41ae-989b-8a6e37c59cc3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n&nbsp\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** _When have you caused something to happen because of an action you took? For example, you flipped a switch, the light turned on._",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6c6f5b48-6013-41ae-989b-8a6e37c59cc3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b2d3115e-39d0-4313-adeb-75b6327847ef"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec16dd09-6508-4dde-876a-66127fb19c9a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n&nbsp\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show the next slide\n\n**Say:** *Let’s see if we can find a pattern here:*\n\n- *When you tap on a device, an app starts.*\n- *When the ball goes in the net, score a point.*\n- *When (event)*, *(action)*.\n\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show the next slide\n\n**Say:** *Normally when we hear “event” we think of:*\n- *Field trip*\n- *Competition*\n- *Birthday Party*\n\n*We’re learning a new meaning for the word \"event\" today.*"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec16dd09-6508-4dde-876a-66127fb19c9a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b2d3115e-39d0-4313-adeb-75b6327847ef"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "59b13280-f743-44b9-830c-d3059fec4425",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "###Vocabulary\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n\n**Say:** *In Computer Science, events cause other actions to happen.*\n\n*This lesson has one new and important vocabulary word:*\n\n- **Event** - An event is an action that causes something to happen."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "59b13280-f743-44b9-830c-d3059fec4425",
        "lesson_activity.key": "b2d3115e-39d0-4313-adeb-75b6327847ef"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1c4ce43d-7893-4dc7-840d-171770b3a7c8",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 1-7 - Skill Building” slide",
        "name": "Events in Bounce",
        "progression_name": "Skill-Building"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1c4ce43d-7893-4dc7-840d-171770b3a7c8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a85d8693-19ad-4bd5-b621-22843f5cc19f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "525802eb-8142-44cf-8b59-f2d9b77fc0dc",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 8 - Free Play” slide",
        "progression_name": "Free Play"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "525802eb-8142-44cf-8b59-f2d9b77fc0dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a85d8693-19ad-4bd5-b621-22843f5cc19f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "835489de-56a6-4379-a3c0-7586d961ddb1",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "####Online Puzzles\n\nAt the end of the set of puzzles, students will have the opportunity to make their game unique. Have the students try new ways to make the game more challenging. For example, try playing with many balls at once, or each time the ball bounces off a wall, launch more balls.",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind the students to only share their work with their close friends or family. For more information watch or show the class ***Pause and Think Online** - Video.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "835489de-56a6-4379-a3c0-7586d961ddb1",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a85d8693-19ad-4bd5-b621-22843f5cc19f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4294885b-a5c0-43f4-b622-f2f5e0d37914",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show the “Events in Bounce” slide\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show the “List these events” slide\n\nHave students record the correct order of events shown on this slide. Call on a few students to share their answers before revealing the \"Answer\" slide. \n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show the “Answer” slide\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show the “How do events work?” slide\n\n\nDiscuss the correct sequence with the class.",
        "name": "How Events Happen",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Although introduced in this lesson, the slide deck ***Events in Bounce - How Do They Happen?** can be applied more generally to express the relationship between hardware and software. Particularly, the final slide simplifies the input-to-output sequence and can be made into a poster for your classroom.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4294885b-a5c0-43f4-b622-f2f5e0d37914",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e50afeca-dd1d-4e02-934c-78f3a30eeb38"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5172b542-501d-4010-8d9e-13944cb57643",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "####Take Me Out to the Ball Game\n\nTake the students outside to play some sort of ball game. Keep track of events and actions. For example, not dribbling in basketball results in a traveling foul and the other team gets the ball. In soccer, kicking the ball out of bounds results in the other team kicking the ball in. Getting the ball to the goal results in a point! Make up more events if your students are into it. Have all of the students yell \"Yippee\" when the captain of one team scores a point. Have everyone fall to the ground and roll around if a student makes two goals in a row!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5172b542-501d-4010-8d9e-13944cb57643",
        "lesson_activity.key": "059d2540-168c-4b44-86ef-4a57fcf2d206"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "fc39d262-33c2-4d8d-9701-8f3166de442c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "###Game Day Commentary (45-60 minutes)\n\n![](https://curriculum.code.org/media/uploads/elaSmall.png) ![](https://curriculum.code.org/media/uploads/mathSmall.png) ![](https://curriculum.code.org/media/uploads/scienceSmall.png) **Computer Science + English Language Arts + Math + Science**\n\n[Game Day Commentary](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1wdBbcgvYXN3GgA1Y2nJjloGosfLxhhWKhUpbQtZPCP0/edit#) is an optional activity aligned to Common Core ELA, Common Core Math and Next Generation Science Standards, written by our teacher community. In this activity, students will read aloud instructions as they learn to code with events in Bounce to make a game. Once the game is complete, students will provide play-by-play commentary as their classmates predict which way the ball will bounce in order to score. Students will also complete a Frayer model about bar graphs prior to creating a scaled bar graph using the data collected during their game.\n\n*Standards Addressed:*\n\n- **CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.RF.3.4:** Read with sufficient accuracy and fluency to support comprehension.\n\n- **CCSS.ELA-LITERACY.SL.3.4:** Report on a topic or text, tell a story, or recount an experience with appropriate facts and relevant, descriptive details, speaking clearly at an understandable pace.\n\n- **CCSS.MATH.CONTENT.3.MD.B.3:** Draw a scaled picture graph and a scaled bar graph to represent a data set with several categories. Solve one- and two-step \"how many more\" and \"how many less\" problems using information presented in scaled bar graphs. \n\n- **NGSS.3-PS2-2:** Make observations and/or measurements of an object’s motion to provide evidence that a pattern can be used to predict future motion. \n\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "fc39d262-33c2-4d8d-9701-8f3166de442c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "1c62e0e3-88c3-4716-9614-8306bc9637b4"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8e26f034-3f3a-47b7-92cb-a049d1f27a8c",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** What is your favorite (classroom appropriate) video game? What is your favorite part of the game?\n\n\nMost of the time, students will respond with some kind of event. When you recognize a student response that describes an event, ask the student to describe it further.\n\nOnce the student is done describing their game, take a minute to relate it back to the definition of an **event**.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
        "name": "Reflect",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you're not quite sure if a student's response describes an event, try to break down the response. Is there an action and a response?\n\nFor example:\n\n - Crossing the finish line and having on screen characters congratulate you\n - Finding a big pot of treasure (or other item) and watching your inventory grow\n - Buying new items from the game's store and having the item to use\n - Pressing the buttons on a game controller and having your character do something cool\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8e26f034-3f3a-47b7-92cb-a049d1f27a8c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ddcb2af4-2de1-4049-b7b8-562a7a9d505b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "57ab1736-ed3a-4478-8201-a1a07aaa139a",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n\n\n - **Event**: An action that causes something to happen.\n\n",
        "name": "Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "57ab1736-ed3a-4478-8201-a1a07aaa139a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ddcb2af4-2de1-4049-b7b8-562a7a9d505b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f753ef6b-ab72-4f54-9882-4f8a4c4707e0",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Pair-Share” slide\n\n\nAsk the students to try and relate some of their favorite parts of video games and how they can be described as events. Have them pair-share and discuss the differences between their events and their partner's.",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f753ef6b-ab72-4f54-9882-4f8a4c4707e0",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ddcb2af4-2de1-4049-b7b8-562a7a9d505b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4aa139c9-4881-4fd6-afc0-5180bff9a444",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "####Online Puzzles\n\nStudents will likely be very excited to make their own _Star Wars_ game at the end of this set of puzzles. If there's time, ask them to plan out what they want the game to do. The  planning and preparation will help the students better recognize the key concepts this lesson is trying to teach. Encourage the students to share and remix each other's games at the end of this lesson.\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Star Wars Project” video",
        "name": "Build a Star Wars Game",
        "progression_name": "Video: Star Wars Project"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4aa139c9-4881-4fd6-afc0-5180bff9a444",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7507fd77-21d9-4ac8-800d-99139daa5c4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "44a8f22d-29b6-4965-9d93-8b0a97df943e",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 2-9 - Skill Building” slide",
        "progression_name": "Skill Building"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "44a8f22d-29b6-4965-9d93-8b0a97df943e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7507fd77-21d9-4ac8-800d-99139daa5c4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f785376c-0dc3-478e-a44d-3126f93f06fd",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Decompose It!” slide\nRemind students to use the skills they've just developed  to make your their own game. They can return to previous levels to remind themselves of what to do step by step\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 10 - Free Play” slide\n\n**Do This:** Show the “Build Your Own _Star Wars_ Game” video at the beginning of Level 10.\n\nLeave time for students to share and remix each other’s games at the end of the lesson.\n\n\n\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Free Play",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Remind the students to only share their work with their close friends or family. For more information watch or show the class: \n\n***Pause and Think Online** - Video.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f785376c-0dc3-478e-a44d-3126f93f06fd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7507fd77-21d9-4ac8-800d-99139daa5c4e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1c9f8b0e-1d88-475e-aa25-67170f9da18e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n \n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n\n**Reflect:**\n\n\n - *What type of game did you create today?* \n- *What did you like about your classmates' games?*",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1c9f8b0e-1d88-475e-aa25-67170f9da18e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "22ca31a8-cf94-4804-b9bc-feb4361a3780"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ae9e91ad-4a7d-4611-8f88-ba91c4c0b78f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Welcome students to class and very briefly introduce the day’s activity.",
        "name": "Setting the Stage\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ae9e91ad-4a7d-4611-8f88-ba91c4c0b78f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f43e7228-bd6e-4060-aee3-71c56510c755"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "915299d4-690b-4c9b-984e-416b3e6807ff",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If you have time and would like to prepare your students with an unplugged activity, consider delivering ***Dance Party: Unplugged** before this lesson. This brief lesson introduces students to the idea of events triggering different dance moves.\n\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
