    {
      "key": "de052275-5511-491f-b103-e66e02777799",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Today we're going to do something really creative. What's your favorite way to be creative?",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "de052275-5511-491f-b103-e66e02777799",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f43e7228-bd6e-4060-aee3-71c56510c755"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "07148413-0106-4740-b24a-1b86afcd3f86",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Encourage students to share the ways they express creativity, such as with art, dance, music, writing."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "07148413-0106-4740-b24a-1b86afcd3f86",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f43e7228-bd6e-4060-aee3-71c56510c755"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "814e63b1-0735-41f3-8c68-c394c7b3463d",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n\n- **Event** - An action that causes something to happen.\n- **Program** - An algorithm that has been coded into something that can be run by a machine.\n- **Code** - (v) to write code, or to write instructions for a computer.\n",
        "name": "Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "814e63b1-0735-41f3-8c68-c394c7b3463d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f43e7228-bd6e-4060-aee3-71c56510c755"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "00daabf8-be6a-4233-8b35-ed1df095868c",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\nExplain that today we're going to be creative with our code. Just like choosing which type of colors of paint to use, or what kinds of words you write with can express creativity, choosing what code you write and how people interact with it can be an opportunity to express your creativity too!\n\n**Get up and dance:** Announce to the class that today we're going to see how we can combine coding with dancing in a creative way. Ask your kids to floss, dab, or do a creative dance move of their own for 10 seconds to get them in the mood. You can play a song from this ***Spotify Playlist** to help kick things off. Capture your class's moves on video.\n\n![](https://curriculum.code.org/media/uploads/girls-flossing.2018-11-01-16_13_52_9Ot0bvX.gif)",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "00daabf8-be6a-4233-8b35-ed1df095868c",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f43e7228-bd6e-4060-aee3-71c56510c755"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2b13c2c8-1a48-45cf-b3b1-fe5346d14b22",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "#### Music Filtering\n\nThis tutorial features songs from popular artists. To get a preview of the song list in this tutorial, check out this ***Spotify Playlist**. We are using radio-safe versions of all songs and for students under 13, we limit the music to this filtered list. If you would like to use the filtered list with older students, you can share ***Spotify Playlist** with your classroom.",
        "name": "Code Your Own Dance Party"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2b13c2c8-1a48-45cf-b3b1-fe5346d14b22",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "54fa2a55-391a-4077-a894-271e00a09c71",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n##### Level 1\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Dance Party Warm Up” video\n",
        "name": "Level by Level Support",
        "progression_name": "Video: Warm Up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "54fa2a55-391a-4077-a894-271e00a09c71",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "96a9bbdc-5fda-423d-ab83-9cbd90dc4c1e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n##### Level 2\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 2 - Practice” slide\n\n\n\n* Drag the red `make a new` block from the toolbox on the left to the workspace on the right. Connect it inside the `setup` block.\n* You have now written your first program. Make sure to press Run to see what happens. You should hear music and see a character start to move in the display area.",
        "progression_name": "Practice"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "96a9bbdc-5fda-423d-ab83-9cbd90dc4c1e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "2f9229bc-d638-4d51-a543-a994a1819862",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n##### Level 3 \n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Dance Party Events” video\nLevel 3\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Video: Events"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2f9229bc-d638-4d51-a543-a994a1819862",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3c75b2f7-997b-4b03-8a18-5701e670e596",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n\n##### Level 4\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 4-5 - Events” slide\n* Levels 4-5 are about making the dance interactive. \n* The green blocks are event blocks. These blocks start a new sequence of code and do not need to be connected inside the `setup` block. \n* Connecting the purple block under the green event block allows you to make the character perform a dance by pressing the orange arrow buttons or keys on your keyboard.\n* Make sure to press the arrow buttons after pressing Run or the dancer(s) won’t move.\n\n##### Level 5\n\n* Make sure to bring out a second purple `do once` block. You should have a `bears do once` block and a `cats do once` block in your workspace. Both should be connected to a green `when pressed` event block.\n* Make sure to press the arrow buttons after pressing Run or the dancers won’t move.\n",
        "progression_name": "Events"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3c75b2f7-997b-4b03-8a18-5701e670e596",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "68c18b64-56ef-482f-bc1d-6e653fac1f2d",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n##### Level 6\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Dance Party Measures” video\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Video: Measures"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "68c18b64-56ef-482f-bc1d-6e653fac1f2d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0311c5c3-f83b-4965-960a-9b81eae7506e",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "##### Level 7\n&nbsp\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 7-9 - Measures” slide\n\n\n\n* Levels 7-8 are about synchronizing the dance to the music. \n* The `after measures` event blocks also start a new sequence of code and should not be connected inside the `setup` block.\n* Connecting the purple `do forever` block under the green `after measures` event block should make the character perform a dance move after the number of measures you indicate.\n* The `do forever` block works differently from the `do once` blocks seen in the previous levels.\n\n##### Level 8\n\n* Make sure to bring out a second green event block.  You should have a `after 4 measures` block and a `after 6 measures` block in your workspace. Both should have purple block connected underneath.\n\n##### Level 9\n\n* Level 9 is about creating groups of dancers quickly.\n* Use the new block provided into the toolbox to create a set of smaller dancers.\n*You should also use the normal `make a new` block to create a larger “lead” dancer.\n* Many students will be familiar with the idea that you can make something seem to be further away by drawing it on a smaller scale. In the next level you’ll be able to fine tune this effect.\n",
        "progression_name": "Measures"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0311c5c3-f83b-4965-960a-9b81eae7506e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "794cdef2-5621-4019-ae8c-b85ef99efbe8",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "##### Level 10\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Dance Party Properties” video\n",
        "progression_name": "Video: Properties"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "794cdef2-5621-4019-ae8c-b85ef99efbe8",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "76bf92a5-d7ff-4350-91f2-5d5d32c9f846",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 11-13 - Properties” slide\n\n##### Level 11\n\n* Levels 11-13 are about adjusting the properties (e.g. size, color) of the dancers.\n* It is important to make sure that the teal `set` block is placed somewhere in the program *after* the dancers have been created. To solve this puzzle, place a `set size` block anywhere in your program and use it to change the size of some of your dancers. \n* Dancers created as a group have a default size of 30. Other dancers have a default size of 100.\n\n##### Level 12\n\n* As with the previous level, make sure to only use the `set tint to (color)` block after you have made the dancers in your program. For example, placing it as the first step in the `setup` area of your program will have no effect.\n\n##### Level 13\n\n* With the right code, you should see the dancer cycle through different colors, sizes, or dance moves.\n* Make sure there is a teal `change`, a teal `randomize` block, or a purple `do forever` block connected inside the `every 2 measures` block. \n* Make sure `do forever` blocks are set to either (Next), (Previous), or (Random). Otherwise, the dancer will just perform the set move repeatedly.\n* Note that the **code students write in this level is not checked for correctness**. This means they will always pass the level, even if they do not change the program. Students should feel free to experiment with their code in ways that are interesting to them. Click the “Finish” button to move on.\n* Making new dancers inside the `every 2 measures` block will cause your program to create multiple identical dancers at the same location(s) and may lead to unintended consequences!\n",
        "progression_name": "Properties"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "76bf92a5-d7ff-4350-91f2-5d5d32c9f846",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ec23bea6-0066-47b2-ab98-9051a125096e",
      "position": 10,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "By this point in the lesson you may notice that the instructions are less prescriptive. Encourage students to be creative and explore the new blocks that are introduced. From this point on student code is **not checked for correctness** in order to encourage experimentation instead of solving a specific task.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ec23bea6-0066-47b2-ab98-9051a125096e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ca27c4da-1bb1-4d53-8ab3-fb7cb0945a3b",
      "position": 11,
      "properties": {
        "description": "##### Level 14\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Dance Party Party On!” video\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Video: Wrap-up"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ca27c4da-1bb1-4d53-8ab3-fb7cb0945a3b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d1bca190-5cee-4166-8d2b-bb71e33d0f01",
      "position": 12,
      "properties": {
        "description": "##### Level 15\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 15 - Free Play” slide\n\n\n* This last level is very open-ended. The tutorial itself is designed to give students ample time to keep working on their own dance.\n* **Encourage Sharing:** If students have cell phones with a data plan they can quickly text a link to their projects to their own phone or a friend's. If your school policy allows it, encourage them to do so here.\n* **Encourage Creativity:** Creativity is important throughout this lesson, but this is true here more than anywhere else!",
        "progression_name": "Free Play"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d1bca190-5cee-4166-8d2b-bb71e33d0f01",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "f10e6b80-4750-4cf6-a310-882718a1ebb4",
      "position": 13,
      "properties": {
        "description": "&nbsp\n####Lesson Extras\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Lesson Extras” slide",
        "progression_name": "Lesson Extras"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "f10e6b80-4750-4cf6-a310-882718a1ebb4",
        "lesson_activity.key": "bc667cef-cc6d-4e50-bfd4-586dada0ee7f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b49878b1-8175-4594-8bf1-07486692dd6e",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** _How does being creative help you program?_\n",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b49878b1-8175-4594-8bf1-07486692dd6e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "25f85008-9a0c-4f82-abc4-c8166ed470a5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bcd43a43-a5d5-4a7b-ba18-550b31e3c04f",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Ask students to add their “Whip Around” sticky notes or note cards to your \"Computer Science\" mind map on their way out the door. Try to populate the board with lots of great ideas about what CS is and why it matters.",
        "duration": "2",
        "name": "Optional Assessment"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bcd43a43-a5d5-4a7b-ba18-550b31e3c04f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "f3b050a9-ff00-4470-ac42-5b6f31adfbc6"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "704566b9-d9ba-4f31-9275-df36b2eb36b9",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n### Survival of the Dancers (45-60 minutes)\n\n![](https://curriculum.code.org/media/uploads/scienceSmall.png) \n**Computer Science + Science**\n\n[Survival of the Dancers](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1F1E-qPyfnh7HV1euIjsRX01PZMhbOAA0q447FqRdefo/edit?usp=sharing)  is an optional activity aligned to Next Generation Science Standards, written by our teacher community. Using Dance Party, students will select at least one organism (dancer) which is well suited for the environment (world) they create. Students are encouraged to utilize the “properties” blocks of code to customize the characteristics of each organism (dancer). \n\n*Standards Addressed:*\n\n- **NGSS.3-LS4-2:** Use evidence to construct an explanation for how the variations in characteristics among individuals of the same species may provide advantages in surviving, finding mates, and reproducing. \n\n- **NGSS.3-LS4-3:** Construct an argument with evidence that in a particular habitat some organisms can survive well, some survive less well, and some cannot survive at all. \n\n- **OPTIONAL EXTENSION: NGSS.3-LS4-4:** Make a claim about the merit of a solution to a problem caused when the environment changes and the types of plants and animals that live there may change.\n\n\n\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "704566b9-d9ba-4f31-9275-df36b2eb36b9",
        "lesson_activity.key": "9795ab4f-89e5-44d5-b3e8-65db1ceef2e9"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "04bc93fd-5d21-415a-8e97-a907a62da6c3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n- Go through some of the terms that might be unfamiliar to students\n- Have students refer back to these definitions throughout the main activity as needed\n",
        "duration": "2",
        "name": "Vocabulary"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "04bc93fd-5d21-415a-8e97-a907a62da6c3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29028945-468f-4b45-a1fc-1828b663269f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "df0ed27b-e93c-4071-90e7-ccc5bc3b30c2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Warm Up” slide\n\n**Discuss:** \n- _Think about an electronic device you use often. For example, a laptop, phone or tablet. What do you think it looks like inside?_\n\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Looking Inside” slide\n\n**Discuss:** \n- _What do you notice?_\n\n**Discussion Goal:** These images show many of the computer parts that students will be using in their skits later in the lesson. This view may be totally new to students and present a new concept they hadn’t considered before - what is inside a computer (or electronic device)? Students may start naming some easily identifiable internal computer parts such as wires. Let students know that by the end of the lesson they will have a much better idea of how everything inside the computer works together!\n\n\n",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Looking Inside"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "df0ed27b-e93c-4071-90e7-ccc5bc3b30c2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "29028945-468f-4b45-a1fc-1828b663269f"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c985185b-cbb9-481c-9574-50f4db87791d",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Preparing Your Skit” slide\n\n**Do This:** Put students into groups of 5 and assign them a skit number from the **<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/1aVJ2CtnvVzde3eDzFOhOWA5f30UTreDZKOSZ2lJ1XYc/template/preview\" target=\"_blank\">skit outline</a>**. Give each student a sheet of paper with their **<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/document/d/19TF1oQThf0ZINZ2Eu37_S_b0aKXDdwVBUm6QnEZLTwc/template/preview\" target=\"_blank\">skit role</a>** on it. First, students should decide who will take on the role of each computer part. Then, students should read through the skit and start brainstorming how they will bring it to life. Finally, students should rehearse their skit and be ready to present it.\n",
        "duration": "15",
        "name": "Preparing your Skit ",
        "progression_name": "Unplugged Activity - Hardware and Software Skits"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c985185b-cbb9-481c-9574-50f4db87791d",
        "lesson_activity.key": "961e24b1-5dd9-4453-b186-366e1ffa9e10"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e16dd3e5-c1fb-4893-9bfc-e55707e74fc5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "progression_name": "Hardware and Software Skits - Student Reminder",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "- Make sure to encourage student creativity. Students can have the freedom to add details to their skit or prepare quick props. Create a positive environment where students will feel comfortable taking a risk by performing the skit.\n\n- Circulate and provide feedback to students emphasizing both strengths and areas for improvement.\nSupport with time management by routinely letting students know how much time is left.\n\n- If you are unable to create even groups of students, a 6th member of a group could be added. The extra person’s role would be the narrator. They can start off the skit by introducing each character and telling what the computer parts are going to work together to do. It can be at the group’s discretion if any extra narration is needed. \n\n- Alternatively, a smaller group could be formed with only 4 members. The “user” role would be eliminated from the skit. The group would creatively decide how to make up for this missing element.\n\n- If you have more students and require extra skit outlines, two groups can work on the same skit. \n\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e16dd3e5-c1fb-4893-9bfc-e55707e74fc5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "961e24b1-5dd9-4453-b186-366e1ffa9e10"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6a43f940-8bd5-4456-9821-5d7d191a8803",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Performing Your Skit” slide\n\n**Do This:** It is up to your discretion how students will present their skits. You may choose based on your knowledge of your class and time constraints. Some ideas:\n\n- Skits could be recorded via video using a computer device. Flip allows students to record and edit videos and then watch their classmates videos. There are settings that allow students to comment and like each others videos. \n\n- Groups could be paired up and show each other their skits. In this option, students perform in front of another small group of peers. The audience is small so stakes are lower. Then they have the opportunity to watch another skit live.\n\n- Groups could volunteer to present to the whole class. Before calling students back to the rug, have groups discuss whether they would like to present in front of everyone. Tell groups that all group members must agree that they wish to present. \n",
        "duration": "20",
        "name": "Performing Your Skit "
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6a43f940-8bd5-4456-9821-5d7d191a8803",
        "lesson_activity.key": "961e24b1-5dd9-4453-b186-366e1ffa9e10"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "8989677a-8a34-4da1-955b-e3655ae4a7dc",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflection” slide\n\n**Do This:** Have students share a glow (positive), grow (constructive feedback), and question they have for another group who performed.",
        "duration": "3",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "8989677a-8a34-4da1-955b-e3655ae4a7dc",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d0fb8a89-943b-4dde-bfb3-d8b91c8da53e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "100da4a6-30b1-4e8e-b5fe-45a7a53ff445",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Do This:** This can be used for an exit ticket or other formative assessment. \n\n**Question:** \n- _What is something new you figured out about an internal or external computer part?_\n",
        "duration": "5",
        "name": "Check For Understanding"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "100da4a6-30b1-4e8e-b5fe-45a7a53ff445",
        "lesson_activity.key": "729a8677-8e3e-4e33-9aa5-82ac6bbd8fbb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "050c1c54-7c38-4ecd-966c-9c119d05c44b",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Model:** Ask for a volunteer and have them stand.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Walk around the table” slide\n- Instruct your volunteer to walk around the table (or their chair, or a friend).\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “next” slide\n- When they finish, instruct them to do it again, using the exact same words you did before.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “next” slide\n- When they finish, instruct again.\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “next” slide\n- Then again.\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** *If you have to tell someone to repeat the same action over and over again, how could you make the directions simpler?*\n\n**Think:** *What if I wanted you to do it ten times? How would you reword my instructions so that they were more efficient and I didn't have to repeat myself so much? Feel free to write your instructions down on a piece of scrap paper.*\n\n**Share:** Ask a few students to share their instructions with the class, pointing out how each approach has simplified the overall approach to giving instructions.\n\n\n**Say:**  *Today we're going to work on finding ways to make giving lots of instructions easier, especially when those instructions repeat themselves a lot.*",
        "name": "Introduction to Loops"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "050c1c54-7c38-4ecd-966c-9c119d05c44b",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4820b656-89ae-42f9-bda3-41de9b66250e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "7d43b763-e8b8-43ef-babb-61715282c7f2",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "###Vocabulary\n&nbsp\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n\n- **Loop** - The action of doing something over and over again.\n\n- **Repeat** - To do something again.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "7d43b763-e8b8-43ef-babb-61715282c7f2",
        "lesson_activity.key": "4820b656-89ae-42f9-bda3-41de9b66250e"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ce76c9f9-8c03-4a5c-8926-e1e574ff06ba",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "####Preview Loops in Ice Age\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Preview - Loops in Ice Age” slide\n\nTo finish the connection, preview an online puzzle (or two) as a class.\n\n**Model:** Reveal an entire online puzzle from the progression to come.  We recommend Puzzle 5.  Point out the \"Play Area\" with _Scrat_ and the acorn, as well as the \"Work Space\" with the Blockly code.  Explain that this Blockly code is now the language that the class will be using to help _Scrat_ get to the acorn.  Do students see any similarities to the exercise that they just did?  What are the big differences?\n\nWork with your class to drag code into the workspace in such a way that _Scrat_ (eventually) gets to the acorn. \n\n**Transition:** Students should now be ready to transition to computers to complete online puzzles on their own."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ce76c9f9-8c03-4a5c-8926-e1e574ff06ba",
        "lesson_activity.key": "2da6bc9b-2ee7-4701-bf04-c17c5575b310"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6750f617-f3c1-44e3-84b4-30ccc6d9d711",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "As students work through the puzzles, see if they can figure out how many blocks they use with a loop vs. without a loop.\n&nbsp\n\n\n",
        "name": "Loops in Ice Age"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6750f617-f3c1-44e3-84b4-30ccc6d9d711",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7ce0c9aa-77b1-47b0-9ddd-4de027d04204"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c74d0052-3fe7-4cd2-9973-e761d59b75c3",
      "position": 2,
