    {
      "key": "e96174ab-1631-47d1-9057-00ca165ee0df",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Show the students the *right* way to help classmates by:\n\n - Don’t sit in the classmate’s chair.\n - Don’t use the classmate’s keyboard.\n - Don’t touch the classmate’s mouse.\n - Make sure the classmate can describe the solution to you out loud before you walk away\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e96174ab-1631-47d1-9057-00ca165ee0df",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7ce0c9aa-77b1-47b0-9ddd-4de027d04204"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6263e80b-807b-4300-a709-e55febd6a8b6",
      "position": 9,
      "properties": {
        "description": "**Circulate:** Teachers play a vital role in computer science education and supporting a collaborative and vibrant classroom environment. During online activities, the role of the teacher is primarily one of encouragement and support. Online lessons are meant to be student-centered, so teachers should avoid stepping in when students get stuck. Some ideas on how to do this are: \n\n - Utilize ***Pause and Think Online** Video whenever possible.\n - Encourage students with questions/challenges to start by asking their partner.\n - Unanswered questions can be escalated to a nearby group, who might already know the solution.\n - Remind students to use the debugging process before you approach.\n - Have students describe the problem that they’re seeing. What is it supposed to do? What does it do? What does that tell you?\n - Remind frustrated students that frustration is a step on the path to learning, and that persistence will pay off.\n - If a student is still stuck after all of this, ask leading questions to get the student to spot an error on their own."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6263e80b-807b-4300-a709-e55febd6a8b6",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7ce0c9aa-77b1-47b0-9ddd-4de027d04204"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "5f3a445c-0cc3-427c-a31b-4236896d0b40",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** *How do loops help you program complex problems?*\n\n\n",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "5f3a445c-0cc3-427c-a31b-4236896d0b40",
        "lesson_activity.key": "d7106028-cf14-42e9-9e41-5a52d982720b"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c3c61eac-a9cb-4271-a6e7-d43131290030",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Use these activities to enhance student learning. They can be used as outside of class activities or other enrichment.\n\n**So Moving**\n\n- Give the students pictures of actions or dance moves that they can do.\n\t- Have students arrange moves and add loops to choreograph their own dance.\n- Share the dances with the rest of the class.\n\n**Connect It Back**\n\n- Find some YouTube videos of popular dances that repeat themselves.\n- Can your class find the loops?\n- Try the same thing with songs!"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c3c61eac-a9cb-4271-a6e7-d43131290030",
        "lesson_activity.key": "c39311e6-8b49-4a2e-9345-c4a72be422b5"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0c8c72d7-4992-424f-8e02-5e9bc6560987",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Students should have had an introduction to loops at this point. Based on what you think your class could benefit from, we recommend:\n\n - Reviewing a puzzle from the last lesson\n - Previewing a puzzle from this lesson\n\nAny of these should help prepare your class for fun with the online puzzles!",
        "name": "Introduction"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0c8c72d7-4992-424f-8e02-5e9bc6560987",
        "lesson_activity.key": "75112dbe-79c2-4ace-af4e-08b9719180bb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "d446e531-56fc-4e3c-af3e-086cbddff904",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** _When should you use a loop in your program?_\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Vocabulary” slide\n\n- **Loop** - The action of doing something over and over again.\n\n- **Repeat** - To do something again.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "d446e531-56fc-4e3c-af3e-086cbddff904",
        "lesson_activity.key": "75112dbe-79c2-4ace-af4e-08b9719180bb"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "61a55443-f6cd-439f-8966-875f257c7722",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "####Online Puzzles\n\nSome students may discover where to add `repeat` loops by writing out the program without loops then circling sections of repetitions. If the students in your class seem like they could benefit from this, have them keep paper and pencils beside them at their computers. Students might also enjoy drawing some of the shapes and figures on paper as they program online."
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "61a55443-f6cd-439f-8966-875f257c7722",
        "lesson_activity.key": "cf2e824b-8262-4ca1-89d1-fd24e9318886"
      }
    },
