    {
      "key": "2a1a21a7-c0c8-4c47-ab7d-1ad307b9cd65",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "####Lesson Extras\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Lesson Extras\" slide",
        "progression_name": "Lesson Extras"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "2a1a21a7-c0c8-4c47-ab7d-1ad307b9cd65",
        "lesson_activity.key": "7d70f80b-922d-4bee-8182-075209bcb340"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "46fbc38b-f0c9-40e9-bcaa-874fa8710dbd",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Discuss” slide",
        "name": "Discussion"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "46fbc38b-f0c9-40e9-bcaa-874fa8710dbd",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e78ae579-2dae-4321-ab56-4ea5964fe785"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bce6d77f-d932-4625-af45-0a6bd95dfce5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\nThere are endless possibilities of coding when using conditions. \n\nNow think about how you would use statements with “while” and “until” in your real life.\n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bce6d77f-d932-4625-af45-0a6bd95dfce5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e78ae579-2dae-4321-ab56-4ea5964fe785"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "b12b9785-68a4-4244-b1d8-631d62745f5e",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** - *What's the difference between an \"until\" loop and a \"while\" loop?*",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "b12b9785-68a4-4244-b1d8-631d62745f5e",
        "lesson_activity.key": "e78ae579-2dae-4321-ab56-4ea5964fe785"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "680c6d57-eee4-4a1d-b9c1-ebcc432c95d3",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** _Today, you'll start the final lesson of the unit, in which you will design and code your own project._\n\n_Before you start, what are three skills or qualities that you think will be important as you complete this project?_\n\n",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "680c6d57-eee4-4a1d-b9c1-ebcc432c95d3",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "3ecb28d1-468d-41fe-8eec-c5cfc2336798",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Get students excited and ready for today's activity!\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “End of Course Project” slide",
        "name": "Planning"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "3ecb28d1-468d-41fe-8eec-c5cfc2336798",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "71d38052-9fa6-4047-a7da-216310f48755",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "We have already had a chance to build a variety of projects. Today, this experience will be much more open-ended, so it will require planning beforehand! \n\n",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "71d38052-9fa6-4047-a7da-216310f48755",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "e1f8017f-fd0f-4ca6-8a79-6700d13e287f",
      "position": 4,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Planning” slide"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "e1f8017f-fd0f-4ca6-8a79-6700d13e287f",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "15cd6ba9-5a3e-4302-a13d-855cba9a2901",
      "position": 5,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\nPlanning is a very important part of coding a game or any other kind of software. So, before we jump onto computers, we will spend some time planning the projects we want to build.",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "15cd6ba9-5a3e-4302-a13d-855cba9a2901",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "0aaf1f23-fe46-456b-b281-146c6ff54a65",
      "position": 6,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Handout: Project Planning Guide” slide\n\n**Distribute**: one ***Project Planning Guide** to each student or pair. With students, go over the steps listed on the guide, then allow them to complete it. Refer to the included exemplar if needed.\n\n- Look at the example projects on Code Studio to get ideas for what you can create! \n\n- A good project will have many different parts. Use the space below to draw and explain how your project will work or what your creation will look like at different points in time.\n\n- Make your project!\n",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "If students are pair programming for this assignment, this warm up is a great opportunity for them to practice sharing and respecting others' ideas. Ensure students are following group work norms you already have in place in your classroom. Otherwise, spend a brief moment going over your expectations.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "0aaf1f23-fe46-456b-b281-146c6ff54a65",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "a3787d87-5241-49f7-9dc8-0d08d56b0469",
      "position": 7,
      "properties": {
        "description": "Sometimes when we create our own projects we find inspiration from other people’s projects. ",
        "remarks": true
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "a3787d87-5241-49f7-9dc8-0d08d56b0469",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bbe70f19-da77-45c0-8edb-826899ff0d0a",
      "position": 8,
      "properties": {
        "description": "If you have gotten permission to remix a project, make sure to give credit to the original coder:\n- If you remix a Code.org project:\n  - Add a comment block that explains where you remixed from.\n  - You might also keep the word “Remix” in the title of your project to tell others that this project originally came from someone else.\n- If you want to remix a friend’s project make sure you get their permission first. Once you get permission, follow the steps above to give them credit.\n\nWhen you don’t have direct permission to remix someone’s project or upload their images into your project, look for publicly available materials instead.\n"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bbe70f19-da77-45c0-8edb-826899ff0d0a",
        "lesson_activity.key": "a5df083d-3957-4f4c-b2a0-7051e3801ecc"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "ffa7f515-b8a4-44a2-8150-424753f66758",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Explore” slide\n\nEquipped with their completed planning guides, students are now ready to bring their projects to life. These levels correspond to the structure of the planning guide, and help navigate students through the process of transforming their ideas into code.",
        "name": "End of Course Project",
        "tips": [
          {
            "type": "teachingTip",
            "markdown": "Students will experience plenty of trial and error while coding. Their projects are likely to become truncated versions of their original scope. Remind students that this kind of compromise is common in software design. It's okay if they don't get to build in every feature they planned!\r\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "ffa7f515-b8a4-44a2-8150-424753f66758",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8324ed09-34ee-48e7-84ac-eedb908f1115"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "1f501796-2875-40da-9f66-0ab8e9bc1bab",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": " \n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 1 - Example Projects” slide\n\n",
        "progression_name": "Example projects"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "1f501796-2875-40da-9f66-0ab8e9bc1bab",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8324ed09-34ee-48e7-84ac-eedb908f1115"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "bbe065b9-7a85-4b63-aa4c-7fb78de39882",
      "position": 3,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Give credit!” slide\n\n**Say:** Sometimes when we create our own projects we find inspiration from other people’s projects. \n\nIf you have gotten permission to remix a project, make sure to give credit to the original coder.\n\n_**If you remix a Code.org project:**_\n 1. Add a comment block that explains where you remixed from.\n 2. You might also keep the word “Remix” in the title of your project to tell others that this project originally came from someone else.\n\n_**If you want to remix a friend’s project:**_\n\nMake sure you get their permission first. Once you get permission, follow the steps above to give them credit.\n\nWhen you don’t have direct permission to remix someone’s project or upload their images into your project, look for publicly available materials instead.\n\n\n&nbsp\n\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Level 2 - Create Your Project” slide\n\n**Say:** _Select one of the four to create your own project._",
        "progression_name": "Create your project"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "bbe065b9-7a85-4b63-aa4c-7fb78de39882",
        "lesson_activity.key": "8324ed09-34ee-48e7-84ac-eedb908f1115"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "c9a9df9e-40c9-49f2-9591-5e72102133ed",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "\n\n&nbsp\n<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Present” slide\n\nTo celebrate students' work, spend the last 10 minutes or so allowing them to showcase their projects. This can be done in many ways, but here are a few:\n\n* **Public Demo**: Select a few exemplary volunteers to briefly demo their projects in front of the class. As they do so, have them touch on what the planning-to-coding experience was like for them, including ideas they'd still like to implement. \n* **Pair Playtesting**: Have students or groups pair up and playtest each other's projects. As they do, ask them to provide positive and constructive feedback to each other. The benefit here is that students will have the opportunity to provide and respond to feedback in a smaller setting. \n* **Gallery Walk**: Ensure all students have their projects ready for testing. Have students move \"musical chairs\"-style to another computer and play/test the project there for a few minutes, until they receive a signal from you to move to another computer. Repeat this every few minutes. While there is less opportunity for structured communication here, this ensures students get to demo as many of their peers' projects as possible.",
        "name": "Showcase\r"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "c9a9df9e-40c9-49f2-9591-5e72102133ed",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ead2a390-b5df-49d5-813a-6a41029bc816"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "6d070cbd-0952-47e1-9b08-b7fdaa29efb5",
      "position": 2,
      "properties": {
        "description": "<i class=\"fa fa-list-alt\" aria-hidden=\"true\"></i> **Display**: Show “Reflect” slide\n\n**Reflect:** *What did you learn in creating this project?\nWhat was the most challenging part about this experience?  How did you overcome that challenge?*\n",
        "name": "Reflection"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "6d070cbd-0952-47e1-9b08-b7fdaa29efb5",
        "lesson_activity.key": "ead2a390-b5df-49d5-813a-6a41029bc816"
      }
    },
    {
      "key": "4976e185-7539-432e-844b-91dc49586284",
      "position": 1,
      "properties": {
        "description": "To build on the skills you learned in CS Fundamentals Course D, [click here to check out Extension Lessons with the micro:bit](https://code.org/maker/csf-microbit).. These 4 micro:bit lessons cover the following topics: Meet your micro:bit, Loops, Conditionals (if...then...else), Inputs and outputs, Events, and Variables.",
        "name": "Extension Lessons with the micro:bit"
      },
      "seeding_key": {
        "activity_section.key": "4976e185-7539-432e-844b-91dc49586284",
        "lesson_activity.key": "78b4be09-32d0-49da-b642-a7dbd7853c95"
      }
    }
  ],
